s still with her children. She shepherded the boys through education decisions and illnesses, eased them into a strange new life, and rejoiced when they embraced unfamiliar winter sports. The letters brim with detail about family holidays, the financial implications of an extended family, their involvement in their church, and the games and activities that kept them occupied. Marie’s letters reflect the lives and concerns of a particular family in Toronto, but they also reveal a portrait of what was then Canada’s second-largest city during wartime. The introduction is by Mary F. Williamson, Marie’s daughter, and Tom Sharp, Margaret’s youngest son. The book features a foreword by Jonathan Vance that puts the letters in historical context.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aWorld War, 1939-1945vPersonal narratives, Canadian. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xChildrenzCanada. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xChildrenzGreat Britain. 0aWorld War, 1939-1945xEvacuation of civilianszGreat Britain. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aHistory: Canadian History. 4aLife Writing. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Historical.2bisacsh1 aSharp, Tom, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aVance, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWilliamson, Mary F., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721940uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978155458322540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781554583225423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781554583225/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgr